[1]
Date: 29 Dec 2006
From: Lars Krusell <LAKR@fvst.dk>

Re the moderator-comments on the latest 2 postings on botulism. They
are very useful and competent, but are missing out 3 important
points; all lessons I learned from the case we had in 2003 in my
food-inspection area (see ProMED posti 20030131.0267).
1. Garlic (and chili) in oil dressing is a known source of _C. botulinum_.
2. Atypical presentation of symptoms occurs with unilateral paresis
and rapid recovery.
3. Botulism may pass undiagnosed in patients with a mild course of
the disease or in patients with atypical symptoms.
All 3 points may be specifically related to _C. botulinum_ type B as
other case stories support. See related articles (summaries) below.
I am a food microbiologist, not a medical doctor, but I was taught at
university that botulism never goes undiagnosed, because it is so
severe in its symptoms and often fatal. This may not always be true.
I learned that it takes a very skilled doctor to diagnose a case of
botulism type B.
ARTICLES ON RELATED OUTBREAKS:
St Louis ME, Peck SH, Bowering D, Morgan GB, Blatherwick J, Banerjee
S, Kettyls GD, Black WA, Milling ME, Hauschild AH, et al. Botulism
from chopped garlic: delayed recognition of a major outbreak. Ann
Intern Med 1988 Mar;108(3):363-8 Enteric Diseases Branch, Centers for
Disease Control, Atlanta, Georgia.
Abstract:
Diagnosis of botulism in 2 teenaged sisters in Montreal led to the
identification of 36 previously unrecognized cases of type B botulism
in persons who had eaten at a restaurant in Vancouver, British
Columbia, during the preceding 6 weeks. A case-control study
implicated a new vehicle for botulism, commercial chopped garlic in
soybean oil (P less than 10(-4)). Relatively mild and slowly
progressive illness, dispersion of patients over at least 8 provinces
and states in 3 countries, and a previously unsuspected vehicle had
contributed to prolonged misdiagnoses, including myasthenia gravis (6
patients), psychiatric disorders (4), stroke (3), and others. Ethnic
background influenced severity of illness: 60 percent of Chinese
patients but only 4 percent of others needed mechanical ventilation
(P less than 10(-3]. Trypsinization of serum was needed to show
toxemia in one patient. Electromyography results with high-frequency
repetitive stimulation corroborated the diagnosis of botulism up to 2
months after onset. Although botulism is a life-threatening disease,
misdiagnosis may be common and large outbreaks can escape recognition
completely.
Morse DL, Pickard LK, Guzewich JJ, Devine BD, Shayegani M.
Garlic-in-oil associated botulism: episode leads to product
modification.Am J Public Health 1990 Nov;80(11):1372-3. Bureau of
Communicable Disease Control, New York State Department of Health and
State University, Albany.
Abstract:
In February 1989, 3 cases of botulism occurred in persons who
consumed garlic bread made from a garlic-in-oil product. Testing of
leftover garlic-in-oil showed it to have a pH of 5.7 and to contain
high concentrations of _Clostridium botulinum_ organisms and toxin.
This was the 2nd episode of botulism associated with a low acid
garlic-in-oil product which needs constant refrigeration. In
response, the Food and Drug Administration has taken steps to prevent
a recurrence by requiring that microbial inhibitors or acidifying
agents be added to such products.
--
Lars Krusell, M.Sc. Food Science
Danish Food Administration, Region Aarhus
<LAKR@fvst.dk>
